class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> combine(int n, int k) {
        vector<vector<int>> result;
        vector<int> current;
        backtrack(result, current, 1, n, k);
        return result;
    }
    void backtrack(vector<vector<int>>& result, vector<int>& current, int start, int n, int k) {
        if (current.size() == k) {
            result.push_back(current);
            return;
        }
        for (int i = start; i <= n; i++) {
            current.push_back(i);
            backtrack(result, current, i + 1, n, k);
            current.pop_back();
        }
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n*k*k!)
space complexity: O(k*n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution uses a recursive backtracking approach. It iterates through numbers from 1 to n, adding each number to the current combination until the combination size reaches k.  The function recursively explores all possible combinations.  The time complexity is dominated by the factorial term due to the exponential growth of combinations. The space complexity is primarily determined by the recursion depth and the size of the generated combinations.

